otu\u00ed respectively. By the beginning of the 18th century, foreign investment from Europeans created a market for the production of cocoa, allowing the locals to gain a new source of income apart from livestock. It was the cocoa market that allowed the community around the Santa Ana monastery to become San Francisco de Macor\u00eds. However, it wasn't until the 1760s that the province gained a monopoly on the cocoa industry or managing to become a town for European travelers to stop by.\n\nThe Villa of Santa Ana of San Francisco de Macor\u00eds also previously called Hato Grande, was named this until it was owned by [[Campuzano Polanco family#Origins|Francisco Ravelo Polanco]], Provincial Mayor of the Santa Hermandad of Santiago de los Caballeros<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eljaya.com/opinion/14498-la-historia-de-la-parroquia-santa-ana-2da-parte|title=La Historia de la Parroquia Santa Ana (2da Parte)|website=ElJaya}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.calameo.com/read/00034521460b5fbedbe91|title=Expansion fundacional y desarrollo en el norte dominicano (1680-1795) (p.154)|last=Hernandez Gonzalez|first=Manuel Vicente}}</ref>, and later the tradition points out to Juan de Alvarado and the families Tejada and De Jesus as the owners of the land and donors of the territorial area for the purpose of its foundation in 1778.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011042036/http://francomacorisanos.com/Historia.aspx|title=Historia de San Francisco de Macor\u00eds}}</ref> \n\nIn 1795, the Treaty of Basel in which Spain ceded to France the whole territory of the Spanish island is signed. France takes over the Spanish side in 1801, and is under French management that a new political division of the island and the city of San Francisco de Macor\u00eds is conceived was assigned a parish. It was assumed that from that moment the council or city council is established, if only we know Minutes of the resolutions of this council since 1811.3\n\nThat's errands General Manuel Maria Castillo that the October 2, 1896, the dictator Ulises Heureaux (Lil\u00eds) became the city of San Francisco de Macor\u00eds in Provincial District \"Peacemaker\" (title that his flatterers called Lil\u00eds). Back then he was assigned as common to Cantonal Position of Matanzas, Section Monte Abajo, Villa Riva, Canton Castillo, among others.\n\nDistrict Peacemaker name lasted until the July 26, 1926, when the Legislature of the Government of General Horacio Vasquez, changed its name to Duarte Province, which remains today.\n\nOn 20 May 1963 the city council approved the renaming of the main streets of San Francisco de Macor\u00eds the request of the Foundation Heroes of Constanza, Maimon and Estero Hondo. The delegation of the integrated Heroes Foundation Mrs. Rosa Elba Carron of Alm\u00e1nzar and Miss Angela Negrette.\n\nThe changes included: Avenida Camilo Av Martyrs;. Cyril Street Castellanos by Saturnino (Nino) Rizek; Av Bolivar Av Frank Grull\u00f3n..; . August 16 by Mr. Leandro Guzman Abreu; Olivier Papi independence; Tonino La Palma street Ach\u00e9car; Welcome Fuertes street Duarte 5; Jaya bridge by Silo Garcia; Puente Quebrada Honda by Guillermo Padilla Hern\u00e1ndez; Ramfis Trujillo park Colonel Juan de Dios Ventura Sim\u00f3.3\n\nCurrently, the leadership of the city jaya is supported on geographic location, potential and diversified natural resources directed to agricultural and livestock production, having as its main sources of domestic consumption and export cocoa and rice, other lines of production and trade; as livestock model in its plains and mountains.\n\nSuch is the leadership, commercial and economic dynamism of the city, the most prestigious industries, companies, trading houses and banks, previous feasibility studies have established branches and representations by road and commercial interconnection with other villages in the city.\n\n==Sites of interest==\n*[[Estadio Julian Javier]]\n*[[Casa del Morris Quezada]]\n*[[Parque Duarte]]\n*[[Catedral de Santa ana]]\n\n== The municipal building ==\n[[File:Ayuntamiento San Francisco de Macoris.jpg|thumb|180px|City Hall of San Francisco de Macoris]]\n\nThe City Hall of San Francisco de Macoris, is the headquarters of the city council and city mayor.\n\n== Santa Ana Cathedral ==\n[[File:CatedralSantaAna2006.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Santa Ana Cathedral]]\nThis structure is a mixture of Gothic and modern architecture.  It covers a complete city block, bound in the north by Santa Ana Street, in the south by Colon Street, on the west by Papi Olivier Street and on the east by Restauracion Street.  The Santa Ana Cathedral is the headquarters of ''Obispo de la Di\u00f3cesis de San Francisco'' and home to the humanist ''Monse\u00f1or [[Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda de Jes\u00fas Moya]].''\n\n== Communications ==\n\nSan Francisco de Macoris, has several radio stations and publications. Its longest running newspaper is ''El Jaya'', which was founded November 20, 1985. Its director and founder is the journalist Adriano Cruz Marte.\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Rafael Molina Ure\u00f1a]]: 44 President of the Republic 1965\n*[[Francisco Garc\u00eda (basketball)|Francisco Garcia]]: [[NBA]] Basketball Player for the [[Sacramento Kings]]\n*[[Juli\u00e1n Javier]]: Baseball Player\n*[[Stan Javier]]: Baseball Player\n*[[Eladio Romero Santos]] Music Producer and Singer\n*[[Marino Vinicio Castillo]]: lawyer\n*[[Hilma Contreras]]: Writer\n*[[Jackeline Estevez]]: Singer\n*[[V\u00edctor Mart\u00ednez (bodybuilder)|Victor Martinez]]: Professional Bodybuilder\n*[[Don Miguelo]]: singer and writer \n*[[Richard Ure\u00f1a]]: Baseball Player\nhttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Vargas\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|San Francisco de Macor\u00eds (Duarte)}}\n{{Provincial capitals of the Dominican Republic}}\n\n{{Municipalities of the Dominican Republic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Francisco De Macoris}}\n[[Category:San Francisco de Macor\u00eds| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Populated places in Duarte Province]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 1490s]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Francisco_de_Macor%C3%ADs"}
{"title_page": "San Clemente Island", "text_new": "{{For|the island in Venice|Isola di San Clemente}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name=San Clemente Island\n|native_name=Kinkipar\n|native_name_link=Tongva language\n| native_name_lang =xgf\n|image_name=San-clemente-island.jpg\n|coordinates={{Coord|32|54|N|118|30|W|scale:250000|display=title,inline}}\n|archipelago=[[Channel Islands (California)]]\n|location=[[Pacific Ocean]]\n|country= {{flag|United States}}\n|country_admin_divisions_1 = {{flag|California}}\n|country_admin_divisions_title_1=[[U.S. state|State]]\n|country_admin_divisions_2=[[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles]]\n|country_admin_divisions_title_2=[[County (United States)|County]]}}\n[[File:Californian Channel Islands map en.png|thumbnail|265px|Map of Channel Islands]]\n'''San Clemente Island''' ([[Tongva language|Tongva]]: ''Kinkipar'')<ref>{{cite web|title=Tongva Place Names|url=http://www.tongvapeople.org/?page_id=696}}</ref> is the southernmost of the [[Channel Islands of California]]. It is owned and operated by the [[United States Navy]],<ref>http://www.scisland.org/</ref> and is a part of [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]]. It is administered by [[Naval Base Coronado]]. Defined by the [[United States Census Bureau]] as [[Census block group|Block Group]] 2 of [[census tract|Census Tract]] 5991 of [[Los Angeles County, California]], it is {{convert|21|mi|km}} long<ref name=\"sci about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scisland.org/aboutsci/aboutsci.html|title=About SCI|access-date=September 19, 2019|publisher=SCIsland.org}}</ref> and contains {{convert|147.13|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of land. The island is officially [[uninhabited island|uninhabited]] as of [[2000 U.S. Census]]. It is estimated, however, that the number of military and civilian personnel present on the island at any given time is at least 300.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-show_geoid=Y&-tree_id=4001&-_caller=geoselect&-context=dt&-errMsg=&-all_geo_types=N&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_G001&-redoLog=true&-transpose=N&-search_map_config=%7Cb%3D50%7Cl%3Den%7Ct%3D4001%7Czf%3D0.0%7Cms%3Dsel_00dec%7Cdw%3D0.3599341050264767%7Cdh%3D0.22748226131046756%7Cdt%3Dgov.census.aff.domain.map.EnglishMapExtent%7Cif%3Dgif%7Ccx%3D-118.42426637496948%7Ccy%3D33.37146458057821%7Czl%3D5%7Cpz%3D5%7Cbo%3D318%3A317%3A316%3A315%3A314%3A313%3A323%3A319%7Cbl%3D362%3A393%3A392%3A358%3A357%3A356%3A355%3A354%7Cft%3D350%3A349%3A335%3A389%3A388%3A332%3A331%7Cfl%3D381%3A403%3A204%3A380%3A369%3A379%3A368%7Cg%3D05000US36061&-PANEL_ID=p_dt_geo_map&-_lang=en&-geo_id=15000US060375991002&-CONTEXT=dt&-format=&-search_results=15000US060375990004&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-keyword= |title=Block Group 2, Census Tract 5991, Los Angeles County |access-date=2020-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105033050/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y |archive-date=2012-01-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The city of [[San Clemente, California|San Clemente]] in [[Orange County, California]] is named after the island.\n\n==Geography==\n===Topography===\nThe island has been generally described as being \"the upper part of a tilted and gently arched northwestward-trending block of the earth's crust that has a straight, steep northeastern slope and a more irregular and much gentler southwestern slope\" that is composed primarily of volcanic rock, with the northeast boundary of the island having a large fault that parallels most of the major faults on the California mainland. San Clemente Island has some of the best examples of marine terraces, and has trench-like canyons, streams, periodic waterfalls, and pools of fresh water.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olmsted |first1=F. H. |title=Contributions to General Geology - Geologic Reconnaissance of San Clemente Island California  (Geological Survey Bulletin 1071-B) |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/1071b/report.pdf |website=pubs.usgs.gov |publisher=U.S. Dept. of the Interior (U.S. Geological Survey) published by U.S. Government Printing Office |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nThis region experiences warm and dry summers and moderate mild falls and winters with no average monthly temperature above 69.5&nbsp;\u00b0F.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, San Clemente Island has a [[Mediterranean climate#Warm-summer Mediterranean climate|warm-summer Mediterranean climate]], abbreviated \"Csb\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=529227&cityname=San+Clemente+Island%2C+California%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for San Clemente Island]</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = San Clemente Island, CA\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 65\n|Feb high F = 64\n|Mar high F = 65\n|Apr high F = 68\n|May high F = 69\n|Jun high F = 71\n|Jul high F = 74\n|Aug high F = 75\n|Sep high F = 75\n|Oct high F = 73\n|Nov high F = 68\n|Dec high F = 65\n|year high F= 69.333\n|Jan low F = 49\n|Feb low F = 50\n|Mar low F = 52\n|Apr low F = 54\n|May low F = 57\n|Jun low F = 60\n|Jul low F = 62\n|Aug low F = 64\n|Sep low F = 63\n|Oct low F = 59\n|Nov low F = 53\n|Dec low F = 49\n|year low F= 56\n|source 1 = Weather.com: {{cite web |title=Monthly weather|url=https://weather.com/weather/monthly/l/San+Clemente+Island+CA+USCA1305:1:US|year=2016 |work=San Clemente Island, CA |accessdate=12 September 2016}}\n|date=\n}}\n\n==Ecology==\n===Fauna and flora===\n\nThe [[San Clemente Island loggerhead shrike]] is an [[endangered species]] that the Navy is taking steps to protect. The [[San Clemente Island fox]] is an [[endemic (ecology)|indigenous]] species.<ref name=\"LAT 2019-12-30\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-12-30/navy-mice-san-clemente-island-emails|title=Mousetraps handed out to sailors at San Clemente Island hotel like 'in-room amenity,' emails say|last=Dyer|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-30|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  [[Feral]] goats roamed the island for centuries, reaching a population of 11,000 in 1972, when their effect on indigenous species was realized. By 1980 the population had been reduced to 4,000. A plan for shooting remaining goats was blocked in court by the [[Fund for Animals]], so the goats were removed with nets and helicopters. The [[San Clemente Island goat]] is a recognized breed of domestic goat.\n\nThe coves around the island are visited by snorkelers  attracted by the abundant sea life, including [[sea lion]]s, [[California spiny lobster|spiny lobsters]], [[hydrocoral]] and [[kelp forest]]s. The island is also home to the endangered San Clemente Island [[Bell's sparrow|sage sparrow]].<ref>[http://ecos.fws.gov/docs/five_year_review/doc2568.pdf San Clemente Island Sage Sparrow]</ref> After decades with no breeding by raptors, because of DDT contamination and Naval activity<ref>{{cite web |title=San Clemente Island Integrated Natural Resources Management Plan | url=http://tierradata.com/sci/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/2002-INRMP.pdf |website=tierradata.com |publisher=Tierra Data Systems, Escondido, CA. |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>, there is now at least one breeding pair of bald eagles<ref> {{cite web |title=Bald Eagle (Haliaeetus leucocephalus) |url=http://www.iws.org/species_bald_eagle_main.html |website=www.iws.org |publisher=Institute for Wildlife Studies |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> and more than one pair of peregrine falcons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Peregrine Falcon (Falco peregrinus anatum) |url=http://www.iws.org/species_peregrine.html |website=iws.org |publisher=Institute for Wildlife Studies |accessdate=20 October 2019 }}</ref> There is a [https://www.youtube.com/embed/KmfaFtU-KRM?autoplay=1 live camera] of the bald eagle nest operated by the [https://www.iws.org Institute for Wildlife Studies] and Explore.org. \n\nIsland flora includes 300 native taxa and approximately 135 non-native taxa with distribution of at least 47 of the island\u2019s native taxa being restricted to two or more of the California Islands, 15 plant taxa being only found on San Clemente Island, and one insular endemic of the island thought to be extinct.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conservation & Research - Channel Islands - San Clemente Island |url=https://www.sbbg.org/conservation-research/channel-islands/san-clemente |website=sbbg.org |publisher=Santa Barbara Botanic Garden |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> The flora of the island includes some plant species found nowhere else in the world. These [[Endemism|endemic]] species include the wildflowers [[Brodiaea kinkiensis|San Clemente Island brodiaea]], [[Triteleia clementina|San Clemente Island triteleia]], [[Lithophragma maximum|San Clemente Island woodland star]], and [[Castilleja grisea|San Clemente Island Indian paintbrush]], and the [[shrub]]s [[Malacothamnus clementinus|San Clemente Island bushmallow]] and [[Munzothamnus|Blair's wirelettuce]]. A unique subspecies of [[Heteromeles|toyon]], ssp. ''macrocarpa'', also grows here,<ref>C. Michael Hogan, (2008) ''Toyon (Heteromeles arbutifolia)'', GlobalTwitcher, ed. N. Stromberg {{cite web |url=http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=84109&lang=us |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719220426/http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=84109&lang=us |archivedate=2009-07-19 }}</ref> as do two rare subspecies of the [[Delphinium variegatum|royal larkspur]].<ref>[http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/ASP/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=1389 Center for Plant Conservation: ''Delphinium variegatum'' ssp. ''thornei'']</ref>\n\n[[Earthworms]] appear to have been introduced in 2008 in soil from the mainland used in a road construction project. In this earthworm-free region, the worms alter the soil and [[microbial communities]] which allows non-native plants to alter the island\u2019s unique ecosystem and threaten [[biodiversity]] that exists there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-earthworms-san-clemente-island-20161007-snap-story.html |title=The lowly earthworm poses a dire threat to this California island |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Louis |last=Sahagun |date= October 7, 2016  |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PSM V48 D732 Musical instruments found on san clemente 1895.jpg|thumb|Illustration by [[Charles Frederick Holder|C. F. Holder]] of Native American bone flutes found on San Clemente Island]]\nArchaeologists have found traces of human occupation on San Clemente Island dating back 10,000 years.\n\nLater inhabitants left trade materials from the northern islands and from the mainland, including [[Coso Volcanic Field|Coso]] [[obsidian]] from the California desert. It has not been established what tribe the recent inhabitants belonged to,\nalthough the [[Tongva people|Tongva]], who are well attested from [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]], are the most likely candidates. The [[Chumash (tribe)|Chumash]], who occupied the northern Channel Islands, may have influenced the inhabitants. Evidence of battles: 'the skeletons of dozens of men piled, one upon another' were also noted on San Clemente and [[San Nicolas Island|San Nicolas]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Holder|first=Fredrick|title=The Channel islands of California: a book for the angler, sportsman, and tourist|year=1910|publisher=A.C McClurg & Co.|location=Stationers' Hall London England|pages=283|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BZkCAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThe first European to sight the island was [[Juan Rodr\u00edguez Cabrillo]] in 1542, who named it ''Victoria''.<ref name=Kelsey>{{cite book\n  | last = Kelsey\n  | first = Harry\n  | title = Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo\n  | publisher = The Huntington Library\n  | year = 1986\n  | location = San Marino\n| page = }}</ref> It was renamed by Spanish explorer [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]], who spotted it on November 23, 1602, [[Clement I|Saint Clement]]'s [[feast day]]. It was used by ranchers, fishermen, and smugglers during the 19th century and into the 20th century.\n\nIn 1835, the [[Whaler|whaleship]] ''Elbe'' of [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], under Captain Josiah B. Whippey (or Whipple), hunted [[sperm whale]]s as far north as \"St. Clements Island\" (San Clemente Island).<ref>{{cite book |last=Webb |first=Robert |title=On the Northwest: Commercial Whaling in the Pacific Northwest 1790\u20131967 |url=https://archive.org/details/onnorthwestcomme0000webb |url-access=registration |year=1988 |publisher=University of British Columbia Press |isbn=0-7748-0292-8 }}</ref> The American steamship ''Lansing'', as well as the [[Schooner|steam-schooner]] ''California'', both anchored in Pyramid Cove, on the south side of San Clemente Island, to process [[Blue whale|blue]], [[fin whale|fin]] and [[humpback whale]]s caught by their \"killer boats\" (steam-driven whale catchers)\u2014the former between 1926<ref>''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 24, 1926); ''Science'', Vol. 64 (July 2, 1926 issue); ''Animal Bulletin: New York Zoological Society'', Vols. 29-30, 1926; ''The Federal Reporter'', 1988; ''American Maritime Cases'', (Vol. 2, 1931).</ref> and 1930,<ref>Townsend, Charles Haskens. 1930. \"Twentieth Century Whaling\". ''Bull. New York Zool. Soc.'', Vol. 33, No. 1; ''California Fish and Game'', ''Fisheries'' (1930); ''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vols. 28-29, 1930-31).</ref> and the latter between 1933<ref>''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 31, 1933).</ref> and 1937.<ref>Nial O'Malley Keyes, ''Blubber Ship'' (1939); Andrew R. Boone, Killer Ships of the Whaling Fleet (''Popular Science'', August 1935); ''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 35, 1937).</ref> In 1935, the Norwegian factory ship ''Esperanza'' caught blue whales as far north as San Clemente Island.<ref>Rice, Dale W. The Blue Whales of the Southeastern North Pacific Ocean (''AFSC Quarterly Report'', 1992).</ref>\n\n[[File:Channel-islands-nasa-space-view.jpg|thumb|View from space of [[Southern California]] coast, showing Santa Catalina Island (closer to mainland) and San Clemente Island (farther from mainland).]]\n\n==Navy base==\n\nThe US Navy acquired the island in 1934. It is the Navy's only remaining ship-to-shore live firing range,{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}} and is the center of the integrated air/land/sea San Clemente Island Range Complex covering 2,620 [[square nautical mile|nm<sup>2</sup>]] (8,990&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>).\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the island was used as a training ground for amphibious landing craft. These small to mid-sized ships were crucial to the island hopping that would be required to attack the islands occupied by the Japanese.\n\nIt is an active [[sonar]] base and has a $21 million simulated city for [[commando]] training.\n\nThere is a US Navy rocket-test facility on San Clemente.  Some [[UGM-27 Polaris|Polaris]]-program test rockets were launched from San Clemente between 1957 and 1960.  The [[SEALAB (United States Navy)|SEALAB III]] project took place off San Clemente in February 1969.\n\nThe US Navy uses the island as an auxiliary naval airfield, [[Naval Auxiliary Landing Field San Clemente Island]]. The main runway 24/06 is used for carrier training by the Navy. Other branches also use this airfield, including the [[United States Coast Guard]].{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}}\n\nAs of the year 2014, San Clemente is home to an auxiliary Air Force base responsible for locating Air Force fighter pilots near the California coast.\n\nThe airfield is home to the [[United States Navy SEALs]] training facilities.{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}}\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nThe island is owned and operated by the [[United States Navy]],<ref>http://www.scisland.org/</ref> and is a part of [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]]. It is administered by [[Naval Base Coronado]]. The [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] (LASD) operates the Avalon Station in [[Avalon, California|Avalon]], [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]], serving San Clemente Island.<ref>{{cite web|title=Avalon Station|url=http://www.lasd.org/stations/for3/avalon/index.html|website=Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department|accessdate=January 21, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217130740/http://www.lasd.org/stations/for3/avalon/index.html|archivedate=February 17, 2010|quote=Avalon Sheriff's Station provides law enforcement for Santa Catalina Island, San Clemente Island, and the ocean waters between the islands and mainland of Southern California.}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:San Clemente Island Sunrise.jpg|Sunrise at Pyramid Point, San Clemente Island\nFile:Bluebanded Gobies.jpg|Bluebanded gobies, San Clemente Island\nFile:California Moray Eel, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|California moray eel, San Clemente Island\nFile:Kelp forest and sardines, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Kelp forest and sardines\nFile:2780_aquaimages.jpg|Giant black sea bass, San Clemente Island\nFile:Giant Black Sea Bass, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Giant black sea bass, San Clemente Island\nFile:Sea Fan.jpg|Sea fan, San Clemente Island\nFile:Hermissenda Nudibranch, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Hermissenda nudibranch, San Clemente Island\nFile:Bat Ray in kelp forest, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Bat ray in kelp forest, San Clemente Island\nFile:Spanish Shawl nudibranch, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Spanish shawl nudibranch\nFile:Swell Shark, San Clemente Island, California.jpg|[[Swellshark]], San Clemente Island\nFile:Swell Shark closeup, San Clemente Island, California.jpg|Swellshark closeup\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|San Clemente Island}}\n{{Portal|Los Angeles}}\n*[http://www.scisland.org/ San Clemente Island]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050127170331/http://fwie.fw.vt.edu/WWW/esis/lists/e101008.htm San Clemente Loggerhead Shrike]\n*[http://www.astronautix.com/s/sanclemente.html Rocket launches at San Clemente]\n*[https://www.scribd.com/doc/131544429/A-Historical-Geography-of-San-Clemente-Island-1542-1935 A very long thesis about the historical geography of San Clemente Island that was funded by the U.S Navy]\n\n{{Greater Los Angeles Area}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Channel Islands of California]]\n[[Category:Islands of Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Islands of Southern California]]\n[[Category:Islands of California]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the island in Venice|Isola di San Clemente}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name=San Clemente Island\n|native_name=Kinkipar\n|native_name_link=Tongva language\n| native_name_lang =xgf\n|image_name=San-clemente-island.jpg\n|coordinates={{Coord|32|54|N|118|30|W|scale:250000|display=title,inline}}\n|archipelago=[[Channel Islands (California)]]\n|location=[[Pacific Ocean]]\n|country= {{flag|United States}}\n|country_admin_divisions_1 = {{flag|California}}\n|country_admin_divisions_title_1=[[U.S. state|State]]\n|country_admin_divisions_2=[[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles]]\n|country_admin_divisions_title_2=[[County (United States)|County]]}}\n[[File:Californian Channel Islands map en.png|thumbnail|265px|Map of Channel Islands]]\n'''San Clemente Island''' ([[Tongva language|Tongva]]: ''Kinkipar'')<ref>{{cite web|title=Tongva Place Names|url=http://www.tongvapeople.org/?page_id=696}}</ref> is the southernmost of the [[Channel Islands of California]]. It is owned and operated by the [[United States Navy]],<ref>http://www.scisland.org/</ref> and is a part of [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]]. It is administered by [[Naval Base Coronado]]. Defined by the [[United States Census Bureau]] as [[Census block group|Block Group]] 2 of [[census tract|Census Tract]] 5991 of [[Los Angeles County, California]], it is {{convert|21|mi|km}} long<ref name=\"sci about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scisland.org/aboutsci/aboutsci.html|title=About SCI|access-date=September 19, 2019|publisher=SCIsland.org}}</ref> and contains {{convert|147.13|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of land. The island is officially [[uninhabited island|uninhabited]] as of [[2000 U.S. Census]]. It is estimated, however, that the number of military and civilian personnel present on the island at any given time is at least 300.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-show_geoid=Y&-tree_id=4001&-_caller=geoselect&-context=dt&-errMsg=&-all_geo_types=N&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_G001&-redoLog=true&-transpose=N&-search_map_config=%7Cb%3D50%7Cl%3Den%7Ct%3D4001%7Czf%3D0.0%7Cms%3Dsel_00dec%7Cdw%3D0.3599341050264767%7Cdh%3D0.22748226131046756%7Cdt%3Dgov.census.aff.domain.map.EnglishMapExtent%7Cif%3Dgif%7Ccx%3D-118.42426637496948%7Ccy%3D33.37146458057821%7Czl%3D5%7Cpz%3D5%7Cbo%3D318%3A317%3A316%3A315%3A314%3A313%3A323%3A319%7Cbl%3D362%3A393%3A392%3A358%3A357%3A356%3A355%3A354%7Cft%3D350%3A349%3A335%3A389%3A388%3A332%3A331%7Cfl%3D381%3A403%3A204%3A380%3A369%3A379%3A368%7Cg%3D05000US36061&-PANEL_ID=p_dt_geo_map&-_lang=en&-geo_id=15000US060375991002&-CONTEXT=dt&-format=&-search_results=15000US060375990004&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-keyword= |title=Block Group 2, Census Tract 5991, Los Angeles County |access-date=2020-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105033050/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y |archive-date=2012-01-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The city of [[San Clemente, California|San Clemente]] in [[Orange County, California]] is named after the island.\n\n==Geography==\n===Topography===\nThe island has been generally described as being \"the upper part of a tilted and gently arched northwestward-trending block of the earth's crust that has a straight, steep northeastern slope and a more irregular and much gentler southwestern slope\" that is composed primarily of volcanic rock, with the northeast boundary of the island having a large fault that parallels most of the major faults on the California mainland. San Clemente Island has some of the best examples of marine terraces, and has trench-like canyons, streams, periodic waterfalls, and pools of fresh water.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olmsted |first1=F. H. |title=Contributions to General Geology - Geologic Reconnaissance of San Clemente Island California  (Geological Survey Bulletin 1071-B) |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/1071b/report.pdf |website=pubs.usgs.gov |publisher=U.S. Dept. of the Interior (U.S. Geological Survey) published by U.S. Government Printing Office |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nThis region experiences warm and dry summers and moderate mild falls and winters with no average monthly temperature above 69.5&nbsp;\u00b0F.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, San Clemente Island has a [[Mediterranean climate#Warm-summer Mediterranean climate|warm-summer Mediterranean climate]], abbreviated \"Csb\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=529227&cityname=San+Clemente+Island%2C+California%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for San Clemente Island]</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = San Clemente Island, CA\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 65\n|Feb high F = 64\n|Mar high F = 65\n|Apr high F = 68\n|May high F = 69\n|Jun high F = 71\n|Jul high F = 74\n|Aug high F = 75\n|Sep high F = 75\n|Oct high F = 73\n|Nov high F = 68\n|Dec high F = 65\n|year high F= 69.333\n|Jan low F = 49\n|Feb low F = 50\n|Mar low F = 52\n|Apr low F = 54\n|May low F = 57\n|Jun low F = 60\n|Jul low F = 62\n|Aug low F = 64\n|Sep low F = 63\n|Oct low F = 59\n|Nov low F = 53\n|Dec low F = 49\n|year low F= 56\n|source 1 = Weather.com: {{cite web |title=Monthly weather|url=https://weather.com/weather/monthly/l/San+Clemente+Island+CA+USCA1305:1:US|year=2016 |work=San Clemente Island, CA |accessdate=12 September 2016}}\n|date=\n}}\n\n==Ecology==\n===Fauna and flora===\n\nThe [[San Clemente Island loggerhead shrike]] is an [[endangered species]] that the Navy is taking steps to protect. The [[San Clemente Island fox]] is an [[endemic (ecology)|indigenous]] species.<ref name=\"LAT 2019-12-30\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-12-30/navy-mice-san-clemente-island-emails|title=Mousetraps handed out to sailors at San Clemente Island hotel like 'in-room amenity,' emails say|last=Dyer|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-30|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  [[Feral]] goats roamed the island for centuries, reaching a population of 11,000 in 1972, when their effect on indigenous species was realized. By 1980 the population had been reduced to 4,000. A plan for shooting remaining goats was blocked in court by the [[Fund for Animals]], so the goats were removed with nets and helicopters. The [[San Clemente Island goat]] is a recognized breed of domestic goat.\n\nThe coves around the island are visited by snorkelers  attracted by the abundant sea life, including [[sea lion]]s, [[California spiny lobster|spiny lobsters]], [[hydrocoral]] and [[kelp forest]]s. The island is also home to the endangered San Clemente Island [[Bell's sparrow|sage sparrow]].<ref>[http://ecos.fws.gov/docs/five_year_review/doc2568.pdf San Clemente Island Sage Sparrow]</ref> After decades with no breeding by raptors, because of DDT contamination and Naval activity<ref>{{cite web |title=San Clemente Island Integrated Natural Resources Management Plan | url=http://tierradata.com/sci/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/2002-INRMP.pdf |website=tierradata.com |publisher=Tierra Data Systems, Escondido, CA. |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>, there is now at least one breeding pair of bald eagles<ref> {{cite web |title=Bald Eagle (Haliaeetus leucocephalus) |url=http://www.iws.org/species_bald_eagle_main.html |website=www.iws.org |publisher=Institute for Wildlife Studies |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> and more than one pair of peregrine falcons<ref>{{cite web |title=Peregrine Falcon (Falco peregrinus anatum) |url=http://www.iws.org/species_peregrine.html |website=iws.org |publisher=Institute for Wildlife Studies |accessdate=20 October 2019 }}</ref>. There is a [https://www.youtube.com/embed/KmfaFtU-KRM?autoplay=1 live camera] of the bald eagle nest operated by the [https://www.iws.org Institute for Wildlife Studies] and Explore.org. \n\nIsland flora includes 300 native taxa and approximately 135 non-native taxa with distribution of at least 47 of the island\u2019s native taxa being restricted to two or more of the California Islands, 15 plant taxa being only found on San Clemente Island, and one insular endemic of the island thought to be extinct.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conservation & Research - Channel Islands - San Clemente Island |url=https://www.sbbg.org/conservation-research/channel-islands/san-clemente |website=sbbg.org |publisher=Santa Barbara Botanic Garden |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> The flora of the island includes some plant species found nowhere else in the world. These [[Endemism|endemic]] species include the wildflowers [[Brodiaea kinkiensis|San Clemente Island brodiaea]], [[Triteleia clementina|San Clemente Island triteleia]], [[Lithophragma maximum|San Clemente Island woodland star]], and [[Castilleja grisea|San Clemente Island Indian paintbrush]], and the [[shrub]]s [[Malacothamnus clementinus|San Clemente Island bushmallow]] and [[Munzothamnus|Blair's wirelettuce]]. A unique subspecies of [[Heteromeles|toyon]], ssp. ''macrocarpa'', also grows here,<ref>C. Michael Hogan, (2008) ''Toyon (Heteromeles arbutifolia)'', GlobalTwitcher, ed. N. Stromberg {{cite web |url=http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=84109&lang=us |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719220426/http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=84109&lang=us |archivedate=2009-07-19 }}</ref> as do two rare subspecies of the [[Delphinium variegatum|royal larkspur]].<ref>[http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/ASP/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=1389 Center for Plant Conservation: ''Delphinium variegatum'' ssp. ''thornei'']</ref>\n\n[[Earthworms]] appear to have been introduced in 2008 in soil from the mainland used in a road construction project. In this earthworm-free region, the worms alter the soil and [[microbial communities]] which allows non-native plants to alter the island\u2019s unique ecosystem and threaten [[biodiversity]] that exists there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-earthworms-san-clemente-island-20161007-snap-story.html |title=The lowly earthworm poses a dire threat to this California island |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Louis |last=Sahagun |date= October 7, 2016  |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PSM V48 D732 Musical instruments found on san clemente 1895.jpg|thumb|Illustration by [[Charles Frederick Holder|C. F. Holder]] of Native American bone flutes found on San Clemente Island]]\nArchaeologists have found traces of human occupation on San Clemente Island dating back 10,000 years.\n\nLater inhabitants left trade materials from the northern islands and from the mainland, including [[Coso Volcanic Field|Coso]] [[obsidian]] from the California desert. It has not been established what tribe the recent inhabitants belonged to,\nalthough the [[Tongva people|Tongva]], who are well attested from [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]], are the most likely candidates. The [[Chumash (tribe)|Chumash]], who occupied the northern Channel Islands, may have influenced the inhabitants. Evidence of battles: 'the skeletons of dozens of men piled, one upon another' were also noted on San Clemente and [[San Nicolas Island|San Nicolas]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Holder|first=Fredrick|title=The Channel islands of California: a book for the angler, sportsman, and tourist|year=1910|publisher=A.C McClurg & Co.|location=Stationers' Hall London England|pages=283|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BZkCAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThe first European to sight the island was [[Juan Rodr\u00edguez Cabrillo]] in 1542, who named it ''Victoria''.<ref name=Kelsey>{{cite book\n  | last = Kelsey\n  | first = Harry\n  | title = Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo\n  | publisher = The Huntington Library\n  | year = 1986\n  | location = San Marino\n| page = }}</ref> It was renamed by Spanish explorer [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]], who spotted it on November 23, 1602, [[Clement I|Saint Clement]]'s [[feast day]]. It was used by ranchers, fishermen, and smugglers during the 19th century and into the 20th century.\n\nIn 1835, the [[Whaler|whaleship]] ''Elbe'' of [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], under Captain Josiah B. Whippey (or Whipple), hunted [[sperm whale]]s as far north as \"St. Clements Island\" (San Clemente Island).<ref>{{cite book |last=Webb |first=Robert |title=On the Northwest: Commercial Whaling in the Pacific Northwest 1790\u20131967 |url=https://archive.org/details/onnorthwestcomme0000webb |url-access=registration |year=1988 |publisher=University of British Columbia Press |isbn=0-7748-0292-8 }}</ref> The American steamship ''Lansing'', as well as the [[Schooner|steam-schooner]] ''California'', both anchored in Pyramid Cove, on the south side of San Clemente Island, to process [[Blue whale|blue]], [[fin whale|fin]] and [[humpback whale]]s caught by their \"killer boats\" (steam-driven whale catchers)\u2014the former between 1926<ref>''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 24, 1926); ''Science'', Vol. 64 (July 2, 1926 issue); ''Animal Bulletin: New York Zoological Society'', Vols. 29-30, 1926; ''The Federal Reporter'', 1988; ''American Maritime Cases'', (Vol. 2, 1931).</ref> and 1930,<ref>Townsend, Charles Haskens. 1930. \"Twentieth Century Whaling\". ''Bull. New York Zool. Soc.'', Vol. 33, No. 1; ''California Fish and Game'', ''Fisheries'' (1930); ''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vols. 28-29, 1930-31).</ref> and the latter between 1933<ref>''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 31, 1933).</ref> and 1937.<ref>Nial O'Malley Keyes, ''Blubber Ship'' (1939); Andrew R. Boone, Killer Ships of the Whaling Fleet (''Popular Science'', August 1935); ''Pacific Fisherman'' (Vol. 35, 1937).</ref> In 1935, the Norwegian factory ship ''Esperanza'' caught blue whales as far north as San Clemente Island.<ref>Rice, Dale W. The Blue Whales of the Southeastern North Pacific Ocean (''AFSC Quarterly Report'', 1992).</ref>\n\n[[File:Channel-islands-nasa-space-view.jpg|thumb|View from space of [[Southern California]] coast, showing Santa Catalina Island (closer to mainland) and San Clemente Island (farther from mainland).]]\n\n==Navy base==\n\nThe US Navy acquired the island in 1934. It is the Navy's only remaining ship-to-shore live firing range,{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}} and is the center of the integrated air/land/sea San Clemente Island Range Complex covering 2,620 [[square nautical mile|nm<sup>2</sup>]] (8,990&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>).\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the island was used as a training ground for amphibious landing craft. These small to mid-sized ships were crucial to the island hopping that would be required to attack the islands occupied by the Japanese.\n\nIt is an active [[sonar]] base and has a $21 million simulated city for [[commando]] training.\n\nThere is a US Navy rocket-test facility on San Clemente.  Some [[UGM-27 Polaris|Polaris]]-program test rockets were launched from San Clemente between 1957 and 1960.  The [[SEALAB (United States Navy)|SEALAB III]] project took place off San Clemente in February 1969.\n\nThe US Navy uses the island as an auxiliary naval airfield, [[Naval Auxiliary Landing Field San Clemente Island]]. The main runway 24/06 is used for carrier training by the Navy. Other branches also use this airfield, including the [[United States Coast Guard]].{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}}\n\nAs of the year 2014, San Clemente is home to an auxiliary Air Force base responsible for locating Air Force fighter pilots near the California coast.\n\nThe airfield is home to the [[United States Navy SEALs]] training facilities.{{r|LAT 2019-12-30}}\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nThe island is owned and operated by the [[United States Navy]],<ref>http://www.scisland.org/</ref> and is a part of [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]]. It is administered by [[Naval Base Coronado]]. The [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] (LASD) operates the Avalon Station in [[Avalon, California|Avalon]], [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]], serving San Clemente Island.<ref>{{cite web|title=Avalon Station|url=http://www.lasd.org/stations/for3/avalon/index.html|website=Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department|accessdate=January 21, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217130740/http://www.lasd.org/stations/for3/avalon/index.html|archivedate=February 17, 2010|quote=Avalon Sheriff's Station provides law enforcement for Santa Catalina Island, San Clemente Island, and the ocean waters between the islands and mainland of Southern California.}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:San Clemente Island Sunrise.jpg|Sunrise at Pyramid Point, San Clemente Island\nFile:Bluebanded Gobies.jpg|Bluebanded gobies, San Clemente Island\nFile:California Moray Eel, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|California moray eel, San Clemente Island\nFile:Kelp forest and sardines, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Kelp forest and sardines\nFile:2780_aquaimages.jpg|Giant black sea bass, San Clemente Island\nFile:Giant Black Sea Bass, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Giant black sea bass, San Clemente Island\nFile:Sea Fan.jpg|Sea fan, San Clemente Island\nFile:Hermissenda Nudibranch, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Hermissenda nudibranch, San Clemente Island\nFile:Bat Ray in kelp forest, San Clemente Island, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Bat ray in kelp forest, San Clemente Island\nFile:Spanish Shawl nudibranch, Channel Islands, California.jpg|Spanish shawl nudibranch\nFile:Swell Shark, San Clemente Island, California.jpg|[[Swellshark]], San Clemente Island\nFile:Swell Shark closeup, San Clemente Island, California.jpg|Swellshark closeup\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|San Clemente Island}}\n{{Portal|Los Angeles}}\n*[http://www.scisland.org/ San Clemente Island]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050127170331/http://fwie.fw.vt.edu/WWW/esis/lists/e101008.htm San Clemente Loggerhead Shrike]\n*[http://www.astronautix.com/s/sanclemente.html Rocket launches at San Clemente]\n*[https://www.scribd.com/doc/131544429/A-Historical-Geography-of-San-Clemente-Island-1542-1935 A very long thesis about the historical geography of San Clemente Island that was funded by the U.S Navy]\n\n{{Greater Los Angeles Area}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Channel Islands of California]]\n[[Category:Islands of Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Islands of Southern California]]\n[[Category:Islands of California]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Clemente_Island"}
