otational tracking, which connects to the smartphone via USB-C or micro-USB. The Gear VR headset also includes a touchpad and back button on the side, as well as a proximity sensor to detect when the headset is on.<ref name=\"samsung\">{{cite web|url=http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/gearvr/gearvr_specs.html|title=Samsung Gear VR - Specs|publisher=samsung.com|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Gear VR was first announced on September 3, 2014<ref name=\"gearvr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.samsung.com/hk_en/news/product/gear-vr/|title= Samsung Explores the World of Mobile Virtual Reality with Gear VR |publisher=samsung.com|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref>. To allow developers to create content for the Gear VR and to allow VR and technology enthusiasts to get early access to the technology, Samsung had released two innovator editions of the Gear VR before the consumer version.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Samsung Gear VR <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zobucks.com.sg/stores/samsung-offers|title=Earn 1.57% Cashback on Samsung Gear VR|last=|first=|date=|website=}}</ref> is designed to work with Samsung\u2019s flagship smartphones. Currently supported are [[Samsung Galaxy S6|Galaxy S6, Galaxy S6 Edge, Galaxy S6 Edge+]], [[Samsung Galaxy Note 5]], [[Samsung Galaxy S7|Galaxy S7, Galaxy S7 Edge]], [[Samsung Galaxy S8|Galaxy S8, Galaxy S8+]], [[Samsung Galaxy Note Fan Edition]], [[Samsung Galaxy Note 8]], [[Samsung Galaxy A8 (2018)|Samsung Galaxy A8/A8+ (2018)]] and [[Samsung Galaxy S9]]/[[Samsung Galaxy S9|Galaxy S9+]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Samsung Gear VR consumer edition goes on sale in the US|url = http://www.trustedreviews.com/news/samsung-gear-vr-consumer-edition-goes-on-sale-in-the-us|website = TrustedReviews|accessdate = November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy Note10, Note10+, Note10 5G, and the Note10+ 5G are not supported by the Gear VR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.androidcentral.com/gear-vr-wont-be-compatible-samsung-galaxy-note-1010|title=The Note 10 isn't compatible with Samsung's Gear VR headset|date=2019-08-08|website=Android Central|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bgr.in/news/samsung-galaxy-note-10-galaxy-note-10-plus-marks-the-end-of-google-daydream-and-gear-vr/|title=Samsung Galaxy Note 10 marks the end of Google Daydream, Gear VR|last=Staff|date=2019-08-14|website=BGR India|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nThe focus can be adjusted using the wheel at the top of the headset. A trackpad is located on the right of the device, home and back buttons are located just above it. Volume can be adjusted through the volume rockers also found on the right hand side. A USB-C port is located on the bottom of the headset.<ref>{{Cite web|title = What are the buttons on my Samsung Gear VR Innovator's Edition, and what do they do?|url = http://www.samsung.com/us/support/answer/ANS00022259/229459/SM-R320NPWSXAR|website = Samsung Electronics America|accessdate = November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome of the major goals Samsung set for this project regarding hardware were: that their headset could support MTP (Motion to Photon) latency less than 20 ms; the optimization of hardware and kernel; and also to create Galaxy Note 4\u2019s QHD display that enables high-resolution rendering in the headset. The lenses field of view are 96\u00b0 for the first three models<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://global.samsungtomorrow.com/gear-vr-how-samsung-makes-virtual-reality-a-reality/|title=Gear VR: How Samsung makes Virtual Reality a Reality|website=Samsung Electronics Official Blog: Samsung Tomorrow|accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/products/samsung/gear/vr/|title=Samsung Gear VR review|website=Engadget UK|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> and 101\u00b0 for the R323.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/products/samsung-gear-vr-2016/|title=Samsung Gear VR review|website=Cnet|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOculus Home is the main facility to download and use content on the Samsung Gear VR. Oculus Home is also the main line for software distribution on the Gear VR. The primary appeal of the Gear VR is for mobile virtual-reality based gaming and simulations, however, recent interest is growing in the effective use of this device in science and medical education<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moro|first=Christian|last2=\u0160tromberga|first2=Zane|last3=Stirling|first3=Allan|date=2017-11-29|title=Virtualisation devices for student learning: Comparison between desktop-based (Oculus Rift) and mobile-based (Gear VR) virtual reality in medical and health science education|url=https://ajet.org.au/index.php/AJET/article/view/3840|journal=Australasian Journal of Educational Technology|language=en|volume=33|issue=6|doi=10.14742/ajet.3840|issn=1449-5554}}</ref>.\n\n== History ==\nAlthough the Samsung Gear VR consumer edition was released in November 2015, Samsung had obtained a patent on a HMD ([[Head-mounted display|Head Mounted Display]]) in January 2005. This was one of the first ideas of using a mobile phone as the display for a HMD. However, mobile phone technology at the time the patent was submitted limited the degree of quality and performance possible. Samsung continued to research VR and HMD internally.\n\nWith the release of the Galaxy S4 in 2013, Samsung formed an official team dedicated to developing a virtual reality based device that would work with a smartphone. While this team developed multiple different prototypes, the performance and display (despite the Galaxy S4 having a Full HD display) were not yet up to standards.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Samsung Gear VR consumer edition goes on sale in the US|url = http://global.samsungtomorrow.com/gear-vr-how-samsung-makes-virtual-reality-a-reality/|website = Trusted Reviews - The Latest Technology News and Reviews|accessdate = November 26, 2015}}</ref> In 2014 Samsung partnered with Oculus (the creators of another well-known virtual reality device, the [[Oculus Rift]]) to help with the development. The Samsung Gear VR was unveiled during the Samsung press conference at IFA Berlin on September 3, 2014 (along with a smartphone capable of running it, the Galaxy Note 4).<ref>{{Cite web|title = IFA 2014: Samsung Galaxy Note 4, Note Edge, Gear VR and Gear S hands-on|url = http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_ifa_2014-review-1126.php|website = GSMArena.com|accessdate = November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Hardware editions ===\n[[File:Samsung GearVR - 2018 (41578196344) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Two women wearing Samsung Gear VR headsets|alt=|left]]\nThe first edition of Samsung's Gear VR, the SM-R320, was released in December 2014. This version was only compatible with the [[Samsung Galaxy Note 4|Galaxy Note 4]]. This edition was mainly released for developers so they could get an understanding of how the device worked and so they could create content which would be ready for the official release of the consumer version of the device. It also gave the chance for VR/technology enthusiasts to gain early access to the technology.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Introducing the Samsung Gear VR Innovator Edition|url = https://www.oculus.com/en-us/blog/introducing-the-samsung-gear-vr-innovator-edition/|website = www.oculus.com|accessdate = November 24, 2015}}</ref> The second edition of Samsung\u2019s Gear VR, the SM-R321, was released in March 2015. This device supports only the [[Samsung Galaxy S6|Galaxy S6]] and the [[Galaxy S6 Edge]]. A micro USB port is also added, to provide additional power to the docked device, as well as a small fan inside to prevent the lens fogging.\n\nThe next edition, SM-R322, was simply referred to as the Samsung Gear VR. It was released on November 20, 2015. Pre-orders for the device went live on Amazon, Bestbuy and Samsung on November 10, 2015 and the device was sold out on the day of release.  This edition has again a few minor changes compared to the previous iterations. First of all this edition supports six Samsung Galaxy devices so far: the S6, S6 edge, [[Samsung Galaxy S6 Edge+|S6 edge+]], Note 5, S7, and S7 edge. It is also 19% lighter than the previous Innovator Edition, it has improved ergonomics and a redesigned touchpad for easier navigation.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Samsung Gear VR now available for pre-orders at $99|url = https://www.oculus.com/en-us/blog/samsung-gear-vr-now-available-for-pre-orders-at-99/|website = www.oculus.com|accessdate = November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe SM-R323 model was released alongside the [[Samsung Galaxy Note 7]], and features minor changes, including an improved field of view, increased cushioning, a flat trackpad, and changes to the cover and body of the device to reduce glare. The model also utilizes [[USB-C]] connector instead of USB Micro-B so that it could be connected to the Note 7. The port is also capable of data transfer. Adapters are provided for use with older devices using micro USB connectors.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Leak: Samsung\u2019s new Gear VR has wider field of view, works with Note 7 |url=https://thenextweb.com/gadgets/2016/08/01/samsung-gear-vr-new/#gref}}</ref><ref name=\"ars-gearvrredesign\">{{cite web|title=New Gear VR redesign doesn\u2019t fix what wasn\u2019t already broken last year|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/08/samsung-gear-vr-2016-review-more-of-the-same-great-portable-vr/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/2/12343650/samsung-gear-vr-usb-c-touchpad-update-price-announced|title=Samsung gives the Gear VR a facelift|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=August 2, 2016|website=The Verge|access-date=October 4, 2016}}</ref> On October 11, 2016, in observance of a [[Samsung Galaxy Note 7#recall|recall and discontinuation]] of the smartphone, the Gear VR was made incompatible with the Galaxy Note 7 for safety reasons.<ref name=\"verge-note7disabled\">{{cite web|title=Oculus disables Gear VR on Galaxy Note 7 over safety fears|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/11/13240098/galaxy-note-7-gear-vr-support-disabled|website=The Verge|accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn updated model, SM-R324, with support for the larger [[Galaxy S8]] was unveiled on 29 March 2017, for release alongside the phone on 21 April 2017. Samsung also unveiled a handheld Gear VR Controller accessory, which is bundled with the updated model, and will be available as a standalone accessory for existing devices. It remains compatible with existing supported devices.<ref name=\"polygon-s8vr\">{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S8\u2019s VR headset delivers refined graphics, so-so controller|url=http://www.polygon.com/2017/3/29/15107024/samsung-galaxy-s8-gear-vr-headset-controller-hands-on|website=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet-newvrs8\">{{cite web|title=Samsung's Gear VR may be the Galaxy S8's greatest fringe benefit|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/samsung-gear-vr-may-be-the-galaxy-s8s-greatest-fringe-benefit/|website=CNET|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn updated model, SM-R325, with support for the larger [[Note 8]] was unveiled on 15 September 2017, for release alongside the phone. Samsung also unveiled a handheld Gear VR Controller accessory, which is bundled with the updated model, and will be available as a standalone accessory for existing devices. It remains compatible with existing supported devices.\n==List of editions and smartphone compatibilities == \n'''Samsung Galaxy VR  (SM-R325)''' <ref name=\"VR edition-list\">{{cite web|title=Which Galaxy smartphones are compatible with which Gear VRs?|url=https://www.samsung.com/uk/support/mobile-devices/which-galaxy-smartphones-are-compatible-with-which-gear-vrs/|website=Samsung|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n* Samsung Galaxy Note 9 (with adaptor from Samsung) Galaxy Note9 is compatible with Gear VR model number SM-R325NZVC*** only <ref name=\"Specifications\">{{cite web|